<p><img style=' float: left; padding: 4px; margin: 0 7px 2px 0;'  class="alignleft  wp-image-306932 noshadow" title="digest - everyday desk - A2" src="http://www.kurzweilai.net/images/digest-everyday-desk-A2.png" alt="" width="263" height="275" />letter | <span style="color: #ff6600;">about the episode from show creators</span></p>
<p>Dear big dreamers,</p>
<p>Olga &amp; Eva here. We hope you&#8217;ll be inspired by our podcast episode no. 59 “Inventor Ray Kurzweil gazes into the future” of our show Dream Big Podcast. He is an inventor, entrepreneur and visionary.</p>
<p>Ray Kurzweil has been described as:</p>
<p>“&#8230; the restless genius” by <em>The Wall Street Journal </em>newspaper<br />
&#8220;&#8230; the ultimate thinking machine” by <em>Forbes</em> magazine<br />
&#8220;&#8230; Edison&#8217;s rightful heir&#8221; by <em>Inc.</em> magazine</p>
<p>That may seem like high praise, but here&#8217;s a tiny sampling of Ray Kurzweil&#8217;s many computer and electronic inventions:</p>
<ul>
<li>the first CCD flat-bed scanner &#8212; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_scanner" target="_blank">link</a></li>
<li>the first omni-font optical character recognition &#8212; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optical_character_recognition" target="_blank">link</a></li>
<li>the first print-to-speech reading machine for the blind &#8212; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reading_machine" target="_blank">link</a></li>
<li>the first commercially marketed, large vocabulary speech recognition &#8212; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speech_recognition" target="_blank">link</a></li>
<li>the first text-to-speech synthesizer &#8212; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speech_synthesis" target="_blank">link</a></li>
<li>the first computer music synthesizer able to re-create the sound of a grand piano &#8212; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kurzweil_Music_Systems" target="_blank">link</a></li>
</ul>
<p>In our podcast guest Ray Kurzweil shares:</p>
<ul>
<li>His BIG DREAM for the future.</li>
<li>What it means to be a futurist, when he realized predicting the future of tech was his dream.</li>
<li>How thinking about the future helps him as an inventor.</li>
<li>How day-dreaming is a source of creative ideas.</li>
<li>How a typewriter inspired 5 year old Ray to invent.</li>
<li>The invention he&#8217;s most proud of, and how it created a huge impact in the lives of blind &amp; vision disabled people.</li>
<li>His new novel for April 2018:<em> Danielle, Chronicles of a Super-Heroine.</em></li>
<li>A little about Danielle, the girl from his novel that dreams about the future.</li>
<li>He explains what “singularity” means, how it will be a turning point in human history.</li>
<li>He explains how human lives will be extended to 100-150 years.</li>
<li>His advice to his 10 year old self.</li>
<li>How he copes with fears.</li>
</ul>
<p>As you can see, Ray Kurzweil is the epitome of a big dreamer, it was a true honor to have him on the show. We’re sure all our big dreamers, kids and adults, will love this episode. Enjoy and DREAM BIG!</p>
<p>&#8212; <em>Olga &amp; Eva Karpman</em><br />
mother &amp; daughter team who created and host the Big Dream Podcast</p>
